-- Oil Options Volatility Declines as Crude Futures Increase
-- B y   D a n   M u r t a u g h
-- 2013-07-12T21:52:21Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-12/oil-options-volatility-declines-as-crude-futures-increase.html
Crude options volatility declined
after underlying futures rose.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options, was 21.78 percent on the  New York  Mercantile
Exchange as of 3:40 p.m., down from 22.21 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for September delivery rose
$1.17, or 1.1 percent, to $105.55. The August contract advanced
$1.04, or 1 percent, to settle at $105.95 a barrel on the Nymex.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
September $100 puts, which fell 30 cents to 98 cents a barrel on
volume of 4,101 lots traded at 3:47 p.m. June $120 calls were
the second-most active, rising 1 cent to 61 cents a barrel on
volume of 3,100 contracts.  Puts accounted for 59 percent of electronic trading volume.
In the prior session, calls made up 52 percent of 215,783
contracts exchanged.  August $100 puts were the most-active options yesterday,
with 9,653 contracts changing hands as they gained 1 cent to 15
cents a barrel. August $112 calls lost 28 cents to 6 cents a
barrel on 8,537 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $80 puts, with
38,962 contracts. Next were December $100 calls with 36,278 lots
and September $90 puts with 36,231.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
